<section class="intro-section mb-12">
    <h3 id="mission">Mission</h3>
    <p>
        <strong>Web Graph</strong> brings the graph / node-link visualization domain into the platform on the
        same terms as every other Web Everything standard, and as a sibling of
        <a href="/projects/webcharts/">Web Charts</a> in the viz family: a graph is declared by its
        <em>semantic intent</em> &mdash; the nodes and edges and what they mean &mdash; kept strictly separate
        from its <em>presentation</em>, which is laid out and drawn natively and themed through
        <a href="/projects/webtheme/">Web Theme</a> tokens. The standard was surfaced by a real gap: the
        plateau-app Platform Map hand-rolls node/graph drawing
        (<code>plateau:src/platform-manager/platform-map.ts</code>), and
        <a href="/backlog/1289-fui-graph-node-viz-block-gap-blocking-plateau-app-platform-m/">#1289</a> ruled
        the gap needs a contract before any Frontier UI build slice &mdash; this project authors that contract.
    </p>
</section>

<section id="scope" class="section-card">
    <h3 id="scope-heading">Scope</h3>
    <p>
        What sets a graph apart from a chart is a positioning <strong>degree of freedom</strong>: a chart
        <em>derives</em> a mark's position from its datum via scales (<code>x = f(field)</code>), but a graph
        <em>invents</em> position via a layout algorithm (layered / force / tree / radial). That extra axis is
        why graph earns its <strong>own project</strong> rather than riding as a webcharts sub-profile, and why
        its renderer seam <strong>splits in two</strong>. The shape is settled &mdash; ratified in
        <a href="/backlog/1352-webgraph-standard-shape-own-project-protocol-seam-count-a11y/">#1352</a>
        (codified at <a href="/docs/agent/platform-decisions.md">platform-decisions &sect; viz-family-shape</a>)
        and scaffolded under epic
        <a href="/backlog/1351-scaffold-the-webgraph-standard-project-graphspec-profile-lay/">#1351</a>.
    </p>
    <div class="standards-grid">
        <div class="standard-card flex flex-col">
            <h4 id="scope-semantic" class="text-lg font-bold m-0 text-gray-900">Semantic plane</h4>
            <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm leading-relaxed mb-0">
                A presentation-free <code>GraphSpec</code> profile describes the graph's meaning &mdash; nodes,
                edges, and their fields &mdash; grounded on the existing
                <code>plateau:src/platform-manager/types.ts</code> <code>GraphNode</code>/<code>GraphEdge</code>
                shapes. <span class="text-gray-400">(Authored in slice B,
                <a href="/backlog/1373-webgraph-slice-b-graphspec-semantic-profile-terms/">#1373</a>.)</span>
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="standard-card flex flex-col">
            <h4 id="scope-presentation" class="text-lg font-bold m-0 text-gray-900">Presentation plane (two seams)</h4>
            <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm leading-relaxed mb-0">
                Because position is <em>invented</em>, the seam splits: a <code>CustomGraphLayout</code> Protocol
                (spec &rarr; positioned coordinates) is independently swappable from a
                <code>CustomGraphRenderer</code> Protocol (positioned + <a href="/projects/webtheme/">Web Theme</a>
                tokens &rarr; output). Defaults are a <strong>deterministic layered-DAG</strong> layout and a
                <strong>native-first SVG</strong> renderer; D3-force / ELK / Cytoscape are adapters behind the
                contracts. <span class="text-gray-400">(Authored in slice C,
                <a href="/backlog/1374-webgraph-slice-c-two-seam-swap-protocol-customgraphlayout-cu/">#1374</a>.)</span>
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="standard-card flex flex-col">
            <h4 id="scope-conformance" class="text-lg font-bold m-0 text-gray-900">Conformance</h4>
            <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm leading-relaxed mb-0">
                A suite scores three axes &mdash; semantic fidelity, theme application, and
                <strong>accessibility</strong> as a first-class axis, with an <strong>adjacency
                description-table</strong> floor (the tier-2 graph-a11y model is researched first).
                <span class="text-gray-400">(Cases in slice D,
                <a href="/backlog/1376-webgraph-slice-d-conformance-cases-3-axes-benchmark-refs/">#1376</a>;
                a11y research in slice E,
                <a href="/backlog/1375-webgraph-slice-e-graph-a11y-model-research-topic-tier-2-grou/">#1375</a>.)</span>
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-blue-50 border-l-4 border-blue-400 p-3 mt-6 text-xs text-blue-800">
        <strong>Status:</strong> concept &mdash; this is the project skeleton (slice A of epic
        <a href="/backlog/1351-scaffold-the-webgraph-standard-project-graphspec-profile-lay/">#1351</a>). The
        <code>GraphSpec</code> profile, the <code>CustomGraphLayout</code> &amp; <code>CustomGraphRenderer</code>
        protocols, the graph-a11y research, and the conformance suite land in the following slices (B&ndash;E).
        Per the constellation rule the contract lives here in <code>@webeverything</code> and the renderer
        runtime ships in Frontier UI.
    </div>
</section>

<section id="graphspec" class="section-card">
    <h3 id="graphspec-profile">GraphSpec Profile</h3>
    <p>
        The portable webgraph artifact is a <strong>GraphSpec</strong> — the thin <strong>semantic core</strong>.
        It declares <em>what the graph means</em> (nodes, edges, and the kind of each) and nothing about
        <em>where anything is drawn</em>: concrete coordinates are <em>invented</em> by a
        <a href="#protocol-custom-graph-layout"><code>CustomGraphLayout</code></a> and the pixels by a
        <a href="#protocol-custom-graph-renderer"><code>CustomGraphRenderer</code></a> consuming
        <a href="/projects/webtheme/">Web Theme</a> tokens. The schema is grounded on the real consumer it
        must reproduce — the <code>GraphNode</code> / <code>GraphEdge</code> shapes in
        <code>plateau:src/platform-manager/types.ts</code> that the Platform Map already hand-rolls. Node
        <code>kind</code>, edge <code>kind</code>, and <code>weight</code> are <strong>semantic</strong>
        encodings — they say <em>"this node is a project, this edge is a dependency, weight this relation"</em>,
        never <code>#3b82f6</code> or an <code>x</code>/<code>y</code>; the resolved palette and size range are
        theme.
    </p>
    {% highlight "typescript" %}
// The portable webgraph artifact — a GraphSpec. SEMANTIC plane ONLY: what the nodes/edges mean. The
// presentation plane (where each node sits, how it is drawn) is invented downstream by CustomGraphLayout
// + CustomGraphRenderer and never appears here. Grounded on plateau's GraphNode/GraphEdge (the Platform
// Map consumer this standard exists to reproduce).
interface GraphSpec {
  nodes: GraphNodeSpec[];
  edges: GraphEdgeSpec[];
  directed?: boolean;          // default true — the layered-DAG default assumes edge direction
  layout?: LayoutStrategy;     // a SEMANTIC hint (which algorithm FAMILY), never coordinates
}

interface GraphNodeSpec {
  id: string;                  // stable join key (project id / provider key / protocol id)
  label?: string;              // the accessible/displayed name — a11y-derivable
  kind?: string;               // semantic category; drives grouping/encoding, resolved style = theme
  group?: string;              // optional cluster/partition membership (a semantic grouping)
}

interface GraphEdgeSpec {
  from: string;                // GraphNodeSpec id
  to: string;                  // GraphNodeSpec id
  label?: string;
  kind?: string;               // semantic relation type (e.g. "depends-on", "provides")
  directed?: boolean;          // per-edge override of the graph-level default
  weight?: number;             // semantic magnitude; the resolved thickness/scale is theme
}

// The native-first default layout family. Position is INVENTED by the algorithm, so the family is a
// swappable dimension: the deterministic `layered` DAG is the conformance-assertable default; `force`
// (non-deterministic) ships as an adapter behind CustomGraphLayout, never as the default.
type LayoutStrategy = 'layered' | 'force' | 'tree' | 'radial';
    {% endhighlight %}
    <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--color-text-muted); margin-top: 1rem;">
        <li><strong>Semantic plane, kept separate:</strong> the spec carries meaning (node/edge <code>kind</code>,
            <code>group</code>, <code>weight</code>), never positions or pixels. A layout + renderer +
            <a href="/projects/webtheme/">Web Theme</a> resolve the presentation, so one spec re-lays-out and
            re-themes without edits.</li>
        <li><strong>Position is <em>invented</em>, not derived:</strong> unlike a chart (where a mark's position
            is <code>x = f(field)</code>), a graph has no positional datum — <code>layout</code> only names the
            algorithm <em>family</em>; <code>CustomGraphLayout</code> computes the coordinates. That extra
            degree of freedom is why the renderer seam splits in two (<a href="/backlog/1352-webgraph-standard-shape-own-project-protocol-seam-count-a11y/">#1352</a>).</li>
        <li><strong>Thin core, additive tiers:</strong> nodes + edges + <code>kind</code> (+ optional
            <code>group</code>/<code>weight</code>) is all the core requires. Nested/compound graphs, ports, and
            multi-edges are additive — a conformant core renderer ignores higher-tier fields gracefully.</li>
        <li><strong>Accessibility is derivable:</strong> node <code>label</code>s + edge relations let the
            tier-1 <a href="#scope-conformance">adjacency description-table</a> a11y floor be generated straight
            from the semantic spec (the tier-2 model is researched in
            <a href="/research/graph-a11y-model/">graph-a11y-model</a>).</li>
        <li><strong>Grounded, not greenfield:</strong> mirrors the shipped
            <code>plateau:src/platform-manager/types.ts</code> <code>GraphNode {id, kind, label}</code> /
            <code>GraphEdge {from, to, kind, confidence, seam}</code> so the standard reproduces a real
            consumer rather than inventing a shape.</li>
    </ul>
</section>

<section id="protocol-custom-graph-layout" class="section-card">
    <h3 id="layout-protocol">CustomGraphLayout Protocol</h3>
    <p>
        Because a graph's position is <em>invented</em>, not derived, the renderer seam <strong>splits in
        two</strong> (<a href="/backlog/1352-webgraph-standard-shape-own-project-protocol-seam-count-a11y/">#1352</a>) —
        and the first half is <code>CustomGraphLayout</code>, the layout-swap contract. A layout takes a
        semantic <a href="#graphspec"><code>GraphSpec</code></a> and produces a <strong>PositionedGraph</strong>
        (node coordinates + optional edge waypoints + bounds) — it computes <em>where</em>, never <em>what</em>
        or <em>how it's drawn</em>. The <strong>native-first default</strong> is a <strong>deterministic
        layered / columnar DAG</strong> (pure: same spec in, same coordinates out, so it is
        conformance-assertable) that Frontier UI ships as the canonical default impl behind this WE contract;
        non-deterministic engines (force-directed) and richer layered engines (ELK / dagre) register as
        adapters — the same impl-swap shape as
        <a href="/projects/webpositioning/#protocol-anchor-positioning">CustomPositioner</a>.
    </p>
    {% highlight "typescript" %}
// The intermediate the two seams hand off — COORDINATES, never semantics. A GraphSpec becomes a
// PositionedGraph; the renderer draws that. Splitting here lets any layout pair with any renderer.
interface PositionedGraph {
  nodes: PositionedNode[];
  edges: PositionedEdge[];
  bounds: { width: number; height: number };
}
interface PositionedNode { id: string; x: number; y: number; width?: number; height?: number; }
interface PositionedEdge { from: string; to: string; waypoints?: { x: number; y: number }[]; }

// The layout-swap contract — the first seam. Consumes the SEMANTIC spec; emits coordinates only.
interface CustomGraphLayout {
  readonly strategy: LayoutStrategy;            // which family this layout implements
  // Deterministic layouts (layered) are the conformance-assertable default; non-deterministic ones
  // (force-directed) ship as adapters, never as the default — same input must give same coordinates.
  readonly deterministic: boolean;
  layout(spec: GraphSpec): PositionedGraph;     // SPEC → coordinates; never draws
}
    {% endhighlight %}
    <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--color-text-muted); margin-top: 1rem;">
        <li><strong>The split is the point:</strong> an independently swappable layout (ELK layered) can pair
            with any renderer, because <code>PositionedGraph</code> is the only thing crossing between the two
            seams — a chart's single-seam <code>CustomChartRenderer</code> precedent does <em>not</em> transfer
            to an invented-position family.</li>
        <li><strong>Deterministic default:</strong> the layered/columnar DAG is pure and assertable; force-directed
            (non-deterministic, hard to test) is an adapter behind this contract, never the baseline.</li>
        <li><strong>Spec is the only lock:</strong> swapping the layered default for an ELK / dagre / D3-force
            adapter leaves the <a href="#graphspec"><code>GraphSpec</code></a> untouched.</li>
    </ul>
</section>

<section id="protocol-custom-graph-renderer" class="section-card">
    <h3 id="renderer-protocol">CustomGraphRenderer Protocol</h3>
    <p>
        The second seam: <code>CustomGraphRenderer</code> takes a <strong>PositionedGraph</strong> (coordinates
        from a <a href="#protocol-custom-graph-layout"><code>CustomGraphLayout</code></a>) plus resolved
        <a href="/projects/webtheme/">Web Theme</a> tokens and produces output. It consumes <em>coordinates +
        theme</em> and never the <a href="#graphspec"><code>GraphSpec</code></a> directly, so swapping the
        renderer leaves both the spec and the layout untouched. The <strong>native-first default</strong> is an
        SVG renderer (labellable — so the a11y axis is reachable, unlike canvas) Frontier UI ships as the
        canonical default impl behind this WE contract; Cytoscape / sigma / canvas adapters register as
        alternatives. Conformance scores <strong>semantic fidelity</strong>, <strong>theme application</strong>,
        and <strong>accessibility</strong> first-class (the tier-1 adjacency description derivable via
        <code>describe()</code>; tier-2 grounded in the
        <a href="/research/graph-a11y-model/">graph-a11y-model</a> research).
    </p>
    {% highlight "typescript" %}
// The draw-swap contract — the second seam. Consumes COORDINATES + theme; never the GraphSpec directly.
interface CustomGraphRenderer {
  render(positioned: PositionedGraph, theme: ResolvedTheme, target: Element): GraphHandle;
}

interface GraphHandle {
  update(positioned: PositionedGraph): void;    // re-draw on a re-layout
  destroy(): void;
  // The adjacency-description a11y text, derivable from the graph — the tier-1 conformance floor.
  describe(): string;
}
    {% endhighlight %}
    <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--color-text-muted); margin-top: 1rem;">
        <li><strong>Native-first, labellable default:</strong> the SVG renderer draws with zero adapters and
            keeps nodes/edges labellable so the a11y axis is reachable; Cytoscape / sigma / canvas are opt-in
            impls behind the same contract.</li>
        <li><strong>Reads coordinates, not the spec:</strong> the renderer never sees the
            <a href="#graphspec"><code>GraphSpec</code></a>, only the <code>PositionedGraph</code> + theme — so
            layout and drawing evolve independently.</li>
        <li><strong>Three-axis conformance:</strong> semantic fidelity (draws every positioned node/edge) +
            theme application (honours <a href="/projects/webtheme/">Web Theme</a> tokens) + accessibility as a
            first-class axis (the <code>describe()</code> adjacency floor).</li>
    </ul>
</section>
